segments.text: Philadelphia and Washington DC.
Why was that so parallel?
Well that was lousy weather that winter and the Air Corps airplanes weren't equipped with good instruments for instruments for instrument flying.
It had no radio aids to tell them when they were on the course and they no de-ices on the airplanes and these poor
They were told to take this mail from here to there and busted right through night and day and nothing, regardless of weather weather.
That's no way to stay alive.
I got out there to Pittsburgh.
The first 60 hours I was out there, I was on duty for 52 hours.
I got eight hours sleep out of 60.
There was another fella out there named Shulgin, and if the weather was doubtful, I'd tell the pilot, go into the hotel in Keysport and get some sleep.
I'd put this damn mail on the train.
So I'd have a little post office out there at the airport.
I'd tell the postmaster, send it into town, put it on the train.
put the airplane in the hangar, wait for some good weather.
The next day, if the weather was decent, I had the pilot to take the plane on back to where I got it.
I stopped all killing out there.
I didn't expedite the air mail particularly, but I kept losing good piloting equipment.
Sure.
Hell with the business of getting it through.
You thought that this idea of getting it through at any cost was foolish?
I thought that the youngster named Shulgin was out there, and he was, I guess, afraid to do anything.
Jones, B.Q.
Jones, knew I would dare to do anything that was necessary, to hell with the higher-ups, including Roosevelt.
And so he sent me out there and I stopped the killing.
What did the postman think about this?
Were they upset because it took longer now?
No.
Post Office Authority, they didn't worry about it.
There's one, I'll show you how bad it was.
It was a little fighter plane, P-12.
Got no, just barely room for the pilot.
There's a little place back at the pilot where he can put his bags, clothing bags.
We come and land in there with mail sacks stacked around the engine, stacked around the cockpit, stuff full back here.
and so damn cold that it got down to 22 below zero that winter.
It was so cold that before we could get that airplane, the mail sacks off, the engine was so cold that we couldn't get it started again.
So, the pilot goes into the hotel to run the airplane down into the
United hangar, I believe, had a hangar there.
United Airlines are very nice to us there, very cooperative.
Put the airplane down there and get it heated up to where we can get it started again the next morning.
That's the kind of equipment we had to carry mail.
The only instruments in a P-12, that's a pursuit airplane, they call them fighter planes nowadays, was the necessary instruments to fly in good weather.
You know, they had a banking turn, you could fly in bad weather, but no de-ices on it at all.
Playing ice, getting iced up,
down here to go.
It was a fiasco.
It did help us get some good equipment later though.
Because the government realized that you were not as well prepared as you should have been?
Yeah.
When people, young

actually get started getting killed you know and losing aircraft and newspapers pick it up and they want to know why of course naturally and then the senators and the representatives start noticing things and then you get some action.
Sure.
Up till then we could yell our heads off and they'd pay no attention to us.
Right.
How long were you there?
I was there until
May, sometime in May.
I finally got back to Boston.
May of 37?
No, May of 34 this was.
We started flying the mail January of 34 and we flew it to May of 34 and then turned it back to the airlines.
And I got back to Boston airport.
I'd been gone seven months on temporary duty.

And when I got back to Boston Airport, I asked Washington to transfer me out of that National Guard squadron over to the reserve detachment that was there on the same airport, where I could at least have something to do.
And so I got over with the reserve, but I still didn't like living in Boston.
Why not?
Oh, I don't like the weather.
I didn't care for the people, particularly.
Not my kind of people.
What do you mean by that?
I don't know.
I just don't seem to think the way I do, and I can't explain that either, because you don't know whether you like somebody or you don't like them.
Here in Del Rio, for instance, we made more friends than we would make in Boston if I lived there 50 years.
I wouldn't try to explain it.
Did they assign you to the National Guard or anything?
I went to the reserves and then I put in to go to Panama in January of 1935.
my friend in the Chief of Air Force office.
Personnel got me signed to Panama.
Went down there in February of 1935.
And by this time you were a captain.
I was a captain at that time and then they started temporary promotions.
We finally got away from the single list and they started
The Air Force, Air Corps, got permission from the powers that be to make temporary promotions.
Well, why is that?
Why do you think?
Well, here I was, I was 19, 35, 18.
That's 17 years.
16 years as a lieutenant and a year as a captain.
and I was doing major work.
I was assigned the commanding officer of the pursuit squadron in Panama the minute I got there.
That was a major's job, so why not make me a major?
Why should we all always be submerged like that?
So it started as temporary.
promotion.
Funny thing, in May I was a lieutenant and I went to captain as 34.
And February 35, ten months, nine months later, I'm a major, a temporary major.
And for some reason they canceled out the temporary business and put me back to captain
for about a week, and then I went back to a major.
They couldn't make up their mind.
I had something wrong.
Then I went to lieutenant colonel in 37, so there's a...
So you went to three grades in three years.
I can show you even worse.
I was 16 years a lieutenant, one year a captain in 1935.
In 1943, I was the burglary general, so that's how fast I went up after they got off this single list.
Did that, getting off the single list and going to the new system of temporary appointments, did that lift morale?
Yeah, it helped.
In 1937, I went to the Command General Staff School, which is an Army school in Fort Leavenworth.
But tell me a little bit about Panama.
What did you think about being down in Panama in the 1930s?
Oh, I loved it.
The weather was fine.
We worked from 7 until noon, and then I had to play polo and got off.
I got to lead several flights.
I led a flight down, headed for Peru one time with a flight of Pursuits, BW-12, Pursuit planes there.
I got down in Columbia, ran into foul weather and I was afraid of losing.
That's just why it would be refreshing, I think.
Go ahead, son, honey.
I'm going to rush you all out to go to lunch about 11.30.
I'm about to lose my voice.
You know, this is wine.
I don't know if you're on a wagon or not.
No, no, no, this is fine.
I got out in Cali, Columbia.

I figured on landing farther down in Columbia on a beach called Tumaco Beach to gas up for the last leg in Guayaquil, Ecuador and the Colombian government decided it was too dangerous to allow us to land on Tumaco Beach and

So, I took the flight down another 100 kilometers to a place called Los Rios and filled up every tank, you know, right to the top and started for the Guayaquil and got out over the ocean and ran into a wall of water and, you know, P-12, the same one that
tell me about flying air mail in.
Not equipped to fight that kind of weather.
We could fly and we could fly on instruments, but here's the Andes Mountains going up to 30,000 feet over here on land and here's the Pacific Ocean with it raining like hell.
I'm gonna lose
some airplanes and pilots here, but I don't go back, so I just turned around and went back into Cali, Columbia, and we spent the night there.
And you didn't lose anybody?
I didn't lose anybody, but I didn't get to Peru, not with that kind of equipment, and I let a flight up to Nicaragua one time.
It was a civilian pilot.
named Kingsley, who was flying from Managua to the mines that were on the northern part of the country.
He had a Ford tri-motor.
And he went down somewhere in the vast forest between Managua and the mines.
And General Somoza, who was president,
about Nicaragua.
I asked Panama to send a flight up there to help find him.
So I took about eight, I was put in charge of the flight, about eight or nine airplanes.
We went up to Managua and searched that area but
You couldn't see, like looking for a needle in a haystack.
Sure.
I remember one time.
It was jungle too, wasn't it?
Yeah, just a big jungle.
You can't see down, you can't see anything.
I remember in Panama, I saw a pilot jump out of an airplane right next to the canal.
I saw exactly where the plane went in.
I flew immediately over there.
to look to see what the plane was and I couldn't never find it.
I knew exactly where it was and I couldn't see it.
It's like, what...
It's a lot of possible.
While we were there, this fellow, Kingsley's brother is searching and he gets lost.
He goes down, so there's two Kingsley brothers, both Americans, lost in that jungle.
I never did find them.
Samosa had us all up at the palace and thanked us and the cocktail party.
Did they die?
Oh, they were gone, yeah.
They never did mine.
So you lost one out of your crew?
No, no.
No, Kingsley, Kingsley's brother went down.
No, I didn't lose any of mine.
All good.
I got them all back to Panama.
And what'd you think of Samosa?
Oh, I liked him.
He was a West Point graduate.
I met his son, who was the one that was run out recently and was murdered down in Paraguay.
I liked him, the family.
How'd they treat you, American Flyers?
They just treated us fine.
They were, well Samosa was very much concerned that these two American Kingsley brothers were lost, but he did the best he could.
He had eight of us up there, eight airplanes from Panama looking for him.
It was an impossible job.
We used to fly up and down Central America.
Goodwill flights.
Oh, really?
During the mid-thirties?
Yeah, 35 or 37.
During Roosevelt's good neighbor policy.
Yeah.
For us, it was just good training and having a good time when we got there.
Did the government
Did the government of the United States give you any instructions?
Or did they just say be friendly?
Well, the first thing I'd do is call on the local ambassador, the American ambassador.
He'd probably be out there to meet us at the airport, you know.
And then we'd go to a cocktail party that night and dinner.
property, embassy, put it on board or something.
Maybe the local chamber of commerce or somebody.
We had a good time.
Did your Spanish improve?
Did I what?
Spanish improve?
Did your Spanish improve?
Oh, yeah.
I got to where I did after a couple of drinks.
I'm losing my tongue.
I bust right into Spanish.
Do you think that the attempt to increase friendly relations between the United States and Central America, was it successful?
Well, I think we did some good.
Maybe not as much as we thought we were, but I think we were certainly welcome.
You were?
Yeah.
Was there any, was there ever any anti-American feeling that you felt?
Never.
Never a bit.
So they were happy to have you, Flyers, as their guest?
They were happy to have us come into the country and make a little excitement for them, you know.
Sure.
Did you put on any air shows like the Air Force did today?
No, no, we didn't put on any air shows for them.
but the feeling at that time was very friendly to Americans in all of those countries.
In Managua, for instance, they took us up one time to where they have a coffee tasting, a coffee wholesale outfit that grades coffee.
They have a big round table that revolves

and they have a coffee expert sitting around this table and each has a little cup and in each cup is a little sample of coffee and so they sit there and pick it off the table and they slurp it up so it hits the roof of their mouth and then quickly spit it out so it doesn't touch their tongue because if it touches their tongue
that would spoil the taste for the next one.
So they slurped it up, hit the roof of the mountain, and spit it out.
The tables moved around, and other cups in front of them.
That's the way they grade coffee.
Actually, that was interesting for you.
That was very interesting for me.
How often did you go on these flights, these goodwill flights?
Oh, I think we would manage about every two months, something like that.
And usually to a different country?
And did you go to all the countries in Latin America?
Yeah.
We usually went all the way up to Guatemala.
We didn't make Mexico, but we'd go up to Guatemala City.
And one time I took a flight over to Salvador.
El Salvador.

We never did stop in Honduras, because I think they were unfriendly to us at that time, but Costa Rica was very friendly, and there's so many Englishmen in Costa Rica, Americans, they speak English mostly everywhere, and they were very friendly to us, and
the other direction towards South America, we never got very far.
That flight I took to Columbia was the only flight we ever made to South America.
Why didn't you go further to South America?
I don't know.
With our equipment, we couldn't get to Peru.
So that left
If we were on the other side, we could probably get to Venezuela by landing at Guadalajara, a port just outside of Caracas.
We could probably get that far.
We might have gotten to Georgetown or British Guiana.
most of the niggers there, so not much point.
And I think they were going communist at the time.
Columbia, we got to Cali, but Bogota, I don't know if our planes would have done so well at that altitude at about five or six thousand feet.
So you didn't want a chance then?
Going north, everything was fine.
Was your main mission in Panama to guard the canals on them?
Yeah.
We were part of the American Army down there.
We were very spit and polish, inspection every Saturday.
I was commanding one pursuit squad on the 31st and I'd take them up every morning and teach dog fighting, simulated dog fighting and things like that.
Did you ever lose any pilots?
We lost a few pilots.
We lost a pilot on cross-country from, night cross-country from the north part of the canal zone back to Albrook, from Fransfield to Albrook.
And this pilot man just dove into the ground, dove into the swamp, killed he and his mechanic.
How'd you get along with the Panamanian people?
They liked their money.
They liked their money.
They had a lot of saloon and things like that in Panama.

Americans would come down there, and they had a union, what they called a union club, and we used to go quite often to have parties there in the union club, and dance half the night, and drink, and spend lots of money in there.
I'm trying to think of the name of that.
Was there ever any
Did you feel ever that there was some anti-Americanism?
No.
None whatever.
I belong to the Panama Golf Club.
I've done it in Panama.
I played with Panamanians and a lot of Americans belong to it.
American civilians.
An American civilian is pro and
We just got along beautifully, correct?
Correct.
What did you think about the recent treaty which gave the Panama Canal... That's one of the worst things Carter did, I think.
I just don't, I just can't understand it.
That's something Carter put over.
He was very anxious to do it.
And I think one of our Texas senators voted for it.
I think Benson voted for it.
Like that.
I don't understand why we should give it away.
I think it was tragic.
Of course, Russia's trying to cut off our communication.
If they can get their hands on the Panama Canal, I severed their communication between west coast and east coast for a Navy, except to go clear out Cape Horn.
And they're trying to close off the Suez Canal by getting into Haley Selassie's country.
Ethiopia.
Ethiopia.
and also on the other side in Yemen, South Yemen, Yemen I guess, where they can flood that off in case of war.
Makes ships go clear out in case of good hope.
Of course, that cuts the communications for your Navy ships.
So you think that was a bad move?
I think it was a bad move.
I think it was instigated by the Communists in Russia.
Mr. Tornadio fell right in for it because he wants to be the dictator there.
He was a dictator in fact.
I think it was Communist inspired.
When did you leave Panama?
I left there in 1937 and went to the command general staff school, where the brass hats go.
Sure, what did you think of that?
Well, when I left Panama they painted one of those helmets they wear in the tropics, they painted brass.
So they presented me with that when I got on the ship.
I liked nine months at Fort Leavenworth, but I wasn't crazy about it.
But I got through quite easily.
Played indoor polo there until I got injured.
I got along okay with the ground officers.
Was it a good learning experience?
Good what?
Learning experience?
I don't know, not learning anything that did me any good.
They were fighting the Civil War over it.
They had these map problems, how you'd get across a stream, you know, where would you put your troops, this, that, and the other.
They called it map problems, once a week.
I used to, you had from one till five on Fridays to do them.
And I'd wrap it up at about 3 o'clock and turn my paper in and I got satisfactory on all of them.
But the rest, most every other officer would stay there and take the full five hours, figuring the longer he took, the better his solution would be.
Well, I decided I'd try that sometime.
So when I had the paper all finished about 3 o'clock,
I said well I'll take the other two hours and I'll go over this again.
So I went through it again and I changed my mind about where I would put my troops and where I would attack from and how I would do it you know.
Turned it in at 5 o'clock and I got a U which meant unsatisfactory.
So from then on to hell with that.
But basically you thought that the school was fighting the past wars, and do you think it was behind times as far as being up to date on modern military tactics?
Ah, mostly.
They did introduce, we had some Air Force, Air Corps instructors there too, and they had what they called a vertical envelopment.
where you drop troops back in the lines, you know, and secure the river crossing or whatever.
But very little of it.
Mostly ground stuff.
Fighting battles in the Civil War, which they should have been fought.
And perhaps some battles over in Europe that
During World War I?
They were fighting some of the World War I battles over here?
Yeah, refighting over here.
You don't sound very enthused about this school.
I wasn't very enthusiastic about it, no.
It was supposed, this school was supposed to educate you for advancement into the general officer corps.
Yeah, advance.
Did you think it was worthwhile?
I don't think it's worthwhile for an Air Force officer, no.
Do you think the school helped your career?
Yeah.
Okay, it's time for you two to go workshop, and then we'll get some lunch.
Well, let's go to the back.
This area is my good area.
I wonder if you can move that chair.
Okay, we're finishing, or we finished on Panama, and then
Your next assignment in 1938, you were sent to Wright-Patterson as a technical, in the technical inspection branch.
Yeah.
Now what were the major problems that needed inspection at that time, do you remember?
At that time, they had three technical, what they called technical supervisors, who traveled twice a year to every Air Force base.
to make sure that the Air Force Base had all technical orders published by Wright-Patterson Air Force Base and that they were following them out.
So they were.
And that they were keeping their aircraft and other machineries in good shape.
And that's what we were inspecting.
I had with me a Master Sergeant
who was a very technical man, and he would check the technical order files and help me look over the aircraft and firefighting equipment, etc.
Sure.
You were making sure that people were maintaining the airplanes properly.
Yeah.
I was on that duty until the war started.
And then my boss in Washington, Barney Giles, called me up and said, you were coming in here to take my place.
I'm going to move up next to General Arnold.
And so I became chief of technical inspection for the entire Air Force.
Right.
Now at Wright-Patterson, before we moved to Washington, at Wright-Patterson, were there
Any major problems with the aircraft?
Anything that you know?
No, no, they are just a question of maintenance.
They are right.
Patterson furnished me an airplane for myself.
Sergeant and I to get around in and they maintained it.
I had it ready to go on or if it wasn't ready, they'd have another airplane for me to take.
And they were very cooperative.
I was working, of course, directly
under the Chief of Air Force.
Wright-Patterson had nothing to do with me except that they maintained my airplane and they gave me office space.
That's the only thing they had to do with me.
Now when you moved to Washington D.C. as the Chief of Technical Inspection for the Air Force, right after Pearl Harbor,
and right after the war started, what were the major problems to get the Army Air Corps ready for the war?
My worst problem was finding good technical inspectors to place in various places with the various air forces and to find airplanes for them to get around in.
Because there was a shortage of airplanes.
A shortage of staff airplanes.
And I went out and I got permission to go out and buy up any civilian aircraft that I thought would be useful for my inspectors to get around in.
And I went over to the Civil Aeronautics Bureau and enlisted all the technical inspectors they would let me have.
which was some help to me.
They were all civilians?
Yes, civilians, inspected.
And were they pretty good?
Yeah, they knew the work, yes.
They were well qualified.
And so in this job, did you travel all over the country inspecting the quality of the Air Force?
Yes, I was on the go quite a bit, sometimes by civilian aircraft.
Sometimes I could pick up an Air Force plane
bowling field and get by myself.
One trip out to Anaheim, California that I made in an Air Force plane, B.C.
When I came back into Washington, the weather was foul and airplanes were stacked up.
The civilian airlines had airplanes stacked up over the

field there waiting their turns to get in, but the controller at the Washington airport gave the bowling field controller in charge, gave him the responsibility of getting me on the ground where bowling, talking me down, you know.
So I got into bowling all right.
Did you, were you able to solve the problem of a shortage of aircraft and inspectors while you were the chief?
No, I was only in that job about nine months.
I was trying to get out of it the minute I got in it.
Why didn't you like that job?
I just didn't like to be close to the throne for one thing, that General Arnold
Every time there was a crack up and somebody was killed, I was on the carpet.
Why?
What causes them?
I told him, but I told him, you are not giving the students enough time before you commission them and give them an airplane.
You ought to extend each primary flying...
basic flying and advanced flying.
Each stage should have one extra week of training before these youngsters are put in an aircraft on their own.
Well, General Arnold, he had the newspapers on his neck all the time.
Roosevelt went, hurry up, hurry up, hurry up.
And so I wasn't able to put that across.
He expected me to go out and find out what caused these wrecks and correct it.
Well, I couldn't do it.
And you kept telling him it was because they weren't trained well enough.
That's absolutely what I told him.
And so I got pretty sick of that.
How did you like General Arnold?
I liked him all right.
I had other generals I liked better.
Why?
Well, General Arnold had his ear...
trained on the White House, Roosevelt, was talking into his ear and the newspapers were on Roosevelt's neck, I guess, and also on Arnold's neck about these crack-ups.
And if I'd been Arnold, I would have told him to shut up and go to hell or do something.
But instead of that, what he tried to make me, the goat,
getting these things, these accidents stopped.
There was no such way I could do it.
So you think he passed the buck too much to you?
Well, he had just, he had a hell of a job, you know, at the start of the war.
I don't, I can't blame him.
Okay.
You also know another person, and that was
General Jeremy Doolittle, what did you think of him?
I think he was probably the best Air Force general we had, really, during the war.
No kidding.
Why do you say that?
He was just a natural born leader.
He could do anything he asked his men to do and do it better.
And he just, he was, men loved to work for him.
They loved to be under him.
I enjoyed my stay with him very much.
He was my type of officer and the main thing is to give a man a job and don't be looking over his shoulder while he's doing it.
Give him the responsibility of the job and if he doesn't do it, we'll find out why and if it happens again, we'll boot him out and get somebody else.
Well that's what, that's Jimmy Doolittle all the way.
And that's the type of leader you were?
Well yeah, I tried to be that way.
In July of 1942, you took an inspection trip, I'll get it right, inspection trip to England.
And what were you inspecting?
You mentioned this in your memoirs, but you don't explain.
I was inspecting the various bases for technical
supervision, technical, how they were getting along from the technical standpoint.
That was my job.
Were there RAF, Royal Air Force bases?
No, they were all American bases.
There was Newfoundland, and there was Labrador.
and two bases in Greenland.
One was called BW-1 and one was called BW-8.
I never found out what the BW stood for.
But one was at the southern tip of Greenland and one was up the west coast of Greenland about a couple hundred kilometers, I guess, up the west coast, up above the Arctic Circle.
And up there they had Colonel Bert Balken, who was a native of Norway,
was up there with the dog team and sleds to go out on the ice cap with Newt and Greenland and rescue any crews that went down on the ice cap.
And he was a man for the job.
He did a fine job on that.
Did he rescue people?
Yeah, he rescued, I don't think we,
I don't recall that we ever lost a crew permanently on that ice cap.
I think we rescued all of them.
Great.
What were the conditions when you did this inspection in July 1942?
What were the conditions?
Very excellent.
Excellent.
Excellent.
Well, that was pretty quick.
Everybody amazed me.
It was in July when the war started in December.
Just six months of May, I had everything working like clockwork.
No kidding.
That's outstanding.
I did an outstanding job.
Now, as you say, you were an inspection, chief of the inspection for just about nine months, and then you volunteered more or less for North Africa.
Yes, I got a hold of Jimmy Doolittle and
in the corridors there of the munitions building and I told him I wanted to get to England in this war.
I said, I spent the last war in this country as a flying instructor and it looks like I'm stuck in Washington here for this one and I want to get out.
And he said, well, have you got somebody to take your place?
And I said, yeah, I got somebody.
He said, all right, I'll put in for you.
And that's the way it happened.
And so he took you on.
Yeah.
And exactly, what was your...
Well, the first week I was over in England the 12th Air Force had not been formed yet completely.

The 8th Air Force was in England and he signed me to the 8th Air Force as Inspector General and I spent a week going around various bases in England to look over how the Americans were doing from a technical standpoint.

and then about a week or ten days while the 12th Air Force was formed for the invasion of Africa with General Doolittle as commanding general, and I was assigned to the A-4 section, which is supply and maintenance.
Okay, so by this time you were a lieutenant colonel, or were you promoted now to colonel?
I was a colonel, I think.
Okay, colonel and...
I just don't know exactly when I was promoted from lieutenant colonel to colonel.
Okay, colonel and the 12th.
Yeah.
And Dulo was the general and commanding officer.
Yeah.
And how many colonels did he have on his staff?
I don't know, but he had General Dunton, who was my immediate boss.
General Dunton was A-4 in charge of supply and maintenance.
And General Dunton had
myself and two other colonels to head up three different sections under him.
